Myth: In the era of the first silence, Elara the Weaver crafted the North Star from a single thread of lunar silver. It was a beacon of absolute precision, a needle that anchored the spinning world to a point of perfect order. However, the mortals below became captives of this clarity. They stood in the valleys like frozen statues, eyes locked onto the silver light, too terrified of the surrounding shadows to take even a single step. They possessed the orientation of gods but the spirit of the stones. 

Kulta, the Fox of the Primal Ember, observed this stillness from the world’s jagged rim. He understood that light without heat is a cold cage. With a defiant bark that shattered the cosmic frost, Kulta leaped into the celestial tapestry. He did not seek to unravel Elara’s thread; instead, he wove his wild spirit into its orbit. His fur, a storm of copper heat, brushed against the silver needle, igniting the static light into cascading ribbons of emerald and violet—the Fox-Fire. This pulse gave the sky a heartbeat. Elara realized that while her star provided the "where," Kulta’s fire provided the "why." Together, they taught that the journey is as sacred as the destination.

